{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486818"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:46:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:46:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.17,0.53,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84697"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84697"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of fatigue, nausea, and vomiting. She has lost 6 kg of weight over this period. She experiences dizziness on standing from bed in the morning and intermittent palpitations throughout the day. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis and autoimmune hypothyroidism. Her medications include levothyroxine and methotrexate. She smokes 10 cigarettes per day and does not consume alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. She has generalised hyperpigmentation of the skin and rheumatoid nodules on her elbows. Her BMI is 20 kg/m\u00b2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24 hour urine free cortisol","Low-dose dexamethasone suppression","ACTH stimulation test","Fasting blood glucose level","CT brain"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison\u0027s disease), including fatigue, gastrointestinal symptoms, postural hypotension, and hyperpigmentation. The presence of other autoimmune conditions (rheumatoid arthritis and hypothyroidism) suggests autoimmune adrenalitis as the likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EACTH stimulation test\u003C/strong\u003E (also called short synacthen test) is the gold standard confirmatory test for primary adrenal insufficiency. Synthetic ACTH (250 \u03bcg) is administered, and cortisol levels are measured at 0 and 30 minutes. In Addison\u0027s disease, there is minimal or no increase in cortisol levels due to adrenal cortex dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24 hour urine free cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elow-dose dexamethasone suppression\u003C/strong\u003E tests are used to diagnose cortisol excess (Cushing\u0027s syndrome), not deficiency. These tests would be inappropriate in this clinical context where adrenal insufficiency is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting blood glucose level\u003C/strong\u003E may be low in Addison\u0027s disease due to cortisol deficiency, but this finding is neither sensitive nor specific enough to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful if secondary adrenal insufficiency from pituitary disease was suspected. However, the presence of hyperpigmentation (due to high ACTH levels) in this case points to primary rather than secondary adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis, morning cortisol and ACTH levels, plasma renin activity, and electrolytes should be checked. CT of the adrenal glands may be considered to exclude infiltrative or infectious causes, though autoimmune adrenalitis is most likely given her other autoimmune conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ACTH stimulation test is the gold standard confirmatory test for primary adrenal insufficiency, measuring cortisol response to synthetic ACTH.","Addison\u0027s disease commonly presents with non-specific symptoms including fatigue, weight loss, postural hypotension, and hyperpigmentation.","Autoimmune adrenalitis is the most common cause of primary adrenal insufficiency and often occurs with other autoimmune conditions."],"references":["Oelkers W. Adrenal insufficiency. N Engl J Med 1996; 335:1206. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199610173351607","Jenkins D, Forsham PH, Laidlaw JC, et al. Use of ACTH in the diagnosis of adrenal cortical insufficiency. Am J Med 1955; 18:3. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/13218033/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68985"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"184"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68985"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T12:07:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T12:07:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84697"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"L